<a name="75768"></a>
<div id="answer-75768" class="answer" data-answerid="75768" >
    <table>
        <tr>
            <td class="votecell">
                

<div class="vote">
    <input type="hidden" value="75768">
    <a class="vote-up-off" title="This answer is useful">up vote</a>
    <span class="vote-count-post ">3</span>
    <a class="vote-down-off" title="This answer is not useful">down vote</a>
    

</div>

            </td>
            


<td class="answercell">
    <div class="post-text"><p>Start by understanding <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/html_node/index.html" rel="nofollow">GNU Make</a>. The online documentation is very useful and no-nonsense.</p>

<p>Meditate on <a href="http://miller.emu.id.au/pmiller/books/rmch/" rel="nofollow">Recursive Make Considered Harmful</a> in order to grok how make is intended to be used.</p>

<p>Then if you start having to check the availability of libraries before starting the compilation, learn <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/autoconf/manual/html_node/index.html" rel="nofollow">Autoconf</a>.</p>

<p>Autoconf will take you a long way. It's reasonably straightforward once you wrap your mind around M4 quoting rules. With autoconf you can detect annoying situations like obsolete broken version of libraries you depend on.</p>

<p>I never needed to go any further. I tried several time to wrap my head around <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/automake/" rel="nofollow">Automake</a>, but it still caused my brain to melt, even after I had years of experience with GNU Make and Autoconf.</p>

<p>There are other funky things like <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/libtool/" rel="nofollow">libtool</a> and <a href="http://pkg-config.freedesktop.org/wiki/" rel="nofollow">pkg-config</a> that can be nice bonus, but it's not something you need to spend time on before you have a clearly identified need.</p>

<p>If your software is internationalized, you <em>need</em> to use <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/gettext/manual/gettext.html" rel="nofollow">gettext</a> too. But i18n is a whole domain, and you <em>will</em> do it wrong if you are not mentored. Fortunately, the i18n community is full of extremely helpful people. </p>
</div>
    <table class="fw">
    <tr>
    <td class="vt">










